3. MIGRATION DECISION: AUTHENTICATION & AUTHORIZATION SERVICES
================================================================================

Framework Criteria Applied:
"Only migrate what generates the cost being optimized. Services that do not
contribute to the primary cost drivers should remain out of scope."

3.1 Amazon Cognito User Pools
   
   RECOMMENDATION: ✅ KEEP OUT OF SCOPE (Do Not Migrate)
   
   Technical Justification:
   
   a) Cost Profile:
      - Cognito charges: $0.0055 per MAU (Monthly Active User) after 50K free tier
      - Current production load: ~1000 MAUs (estimated from store scale)
      - Monthly cost: $5.50 (negligible)
      - Lambda invocation cost for auth: Minimal (authorizer cached)
   
   b) Operational Benefits:
      - Managed service: Zero maintenance overhead
      - Built-in security: JWT verification, password policies, MFA support
      - Compliance: SOC2, PCI DSS, HIPAA eligible
      - Scalability: Auto-scales to millions of users
      - Features: Email verification, password reset, OAuth2/OIDC
   
   c) Migration Complexity:
      - High: Would require implementing user management system
      - Database schema: users, passwords (hashed), sessions, tokens
      - Security concerns: Password hashing, token generation/validation
      - Features to replicate: Email verification, password reset flows
      - Estimated effort: 3-4 weeks development + security audit
   
   d) IaaS Alternative Cost:
      - RDS storage for user data: ~$15/month
      - Application server resources: Marginal increase
      - Security maintenance: Ongoing effort
      - Total: Higher cost + operational burden
   
   e) Risk Assessment:
      - LOW risk keeping Cognito (mature, stable service)
      - HIGH risk migrating (security vulnerabilities, compliance issues)
   
   Migration Impact:
   - IaaS application will integrate with Cognito via AWS SDK
   - JWT verification remains at application layer
   - User groups/attributes stay in Cognito
   - No database migration required

3.2 AWS Verified Permissions (AVP)
   
   RECOMMENDATION: ✅ MIGRATE TO IAAS (Replace with Application Logic)
   
   Technical Justification:
   
   a) Cost Profile:
      - AVP charges: $0.50 per 10K authorization requests
      - Current production load: ~500K requests/day (estimated)
      - Monthly cost: ~$750 (significant)
      - Lambda authorizer invocations: ~$200/month
      - Total auth cost: ~$950/month
   
   b) Architectural Concerns:
      - Lambda authorizer adds latency: ~200-300ms per request
      - AVP IsAuthorized API call: ~50-100ms additional latency
      - Total overhead: 250-400ms for every store operation
      - This is the PRIMARY performance bottleneck in FaaS
   
   c) Migration Feasibility:
      - LOW complexity: Cedar policies can be translated to code
      - Policy logic is simple: Group-based + attribute checks
      - Already have clear policy definitions in policySamples.json
      - Can implement as middleware in Express.js/NestJS
   
   d) IaaS Alternative:
      - Implement as application-layer authorization middleware
      - Use RBAC (Role-Based Access Control) pattern
      - Store user roles in Cognito groups (already exists)
      - Attribute checks using custom claims (already exists)
      - Estimated implementation: 1-2 weeks
   
   e) Performance Improvement:
      - Remove Lambda authorizer: -200ms latency
      - Remove AVP API call: -100ms latency
      - Direct authorization: <10ms (in-memory check)
      - Net improvement: 290ms faster per request
   
   f) Cost Savings:
      - AVP cost eliminated: -$750/month
      - Lambda authorizer cost eliminated: -$200/month
      - Total savings: $950/month = $11,400/year
   
   Migration Strategy:
   - Translate Cedar policies to middleware functions
   - Use decorator pattern for route protection
   - Implement authorization checks in business logic layer
   - Cache user permissions in session/JWT
   - Remove Lambda authorizer from API Gateway

3.3 API Key Authentication (API Gateway + SSM)
   
   RECOMMENDATION: ✅ KEEP HYBRID APPROACH
   
   Technical Justification:
   
   a) Current Implementation:
      - API Gateway validates API key (no Lambda overhead)
      - SSM stores key value (encrypted)
      - Usage Plans enforce rate limiting
      - Cost: Negligible (~$0.50/month SSM parameter)
   
   b) Migration Decision:
      - Admin endpoints will exist in IaaS monolith
      - Can keep API key validation at application layer
      - Alternative: Use same Cognito with admin group
   
   c) Recommended Approach:
      - Migrate to Cognito-based auth for consistency
      - Create "Admin" group in Cognito
      - Remove API key dependency
      - Simplify authentication model (single mechanism)
      - Cost impact: Zero (same Cognito MAU)

3.4 Lambda Authorizer (petstoreAuthorizer)
   
   RECOMMENDATION: ❌ ELIMINATE (No Longer Needed)
   
   Technical Justification:
   
   a) Current Role:
      - Verifies Cognito JWT (will move to application layer)
      - Queries AVP (being eliminated)
      - Fetches store/franchise data (unnecessary with direct DB access)
      - Generates IAM policy (API Gateway specific)
   
   b) IaaS Replacement:
      - Express.js/NestJS middleware for JWT verification
      - Application-layer authorization logic
      - Direct database access (no need to call admin APIs)
      - In-memory entity relationships
   
   c) Cost Savings:
      - Lambda invocations eliminated: -$200/month
      - Latency reduction: -200ms per request
   
   d) Implementation:
      - JWT verification: Use aws-jwt-verify library (same as authorizer)
      - Authorization: Middleware functions
      - Entity resolution: Direct database queries

