7. GAPS AND LIMITATIONS
================================================================================

7.1 Missing Implementations

Issue: Store Lambda Does Not Perform CRUD
   Description: The petstoresample78b39c63 Lambda only performs authorization
                checks via AVP. It does not actually create, read, update, or
                delete pet/order records.
   Impact: IaaS migration must implement actual CRUD operations for pets and orders.
   Evidence: Lambda handler returns authorization response, not data.

Issue: Pet/Order Data Schema Not Defined
   Description: No actual database schema or storage implementation for pets/orders
                was found in the Lambda code.
   Impact: IaaS migration must design and implement pet/order storage.
   Workaround: Schemas inferred from AVP policy schema and domain knowledge.

7.2 REST Convention Violations

Issue: Non-Standard HTTP Methods
   Routes:
   - POST /store/{storeId}/pet/update/{petId} (should be PUT)
   - POST /store/{storeId}/order/cancel/{orderNumber} (should be DELETE)
   
   Recommendation: IaaS implementation should follow REST conventions:
   - PUT /store/{storeId}/pet/{petId}
   - DELETE /store/{storeId}/order/{orderNumber}

7.3 Unmapped Authorization Actions

Issue: GET /store/{storeId}/pet/get/{petId} Not in actionMap
   Description: This endpoint is defined in API Gateway (cli-inputs.json)
                but not mapped to an AVP action in the authorizer code.
   Impact: Endpoint likely returns 403 Forbidden for all requests.
   Recommendation: Implement proper authorization in IaaS version.

================================================================================
8. MIGRATION RECOMMENDATIONS
================================================================================

8.1 Keep Out of Scope
   ✅ Amazon Cognito User Pools
      - Reason: Cost-effective, managed service
      - Integration: IaaS app validates JWT tokens
      - Savings: Avoids security implementation effort
   
   ✅ AWS SSM Parameter Store (for configuration)
      - Reason: Minimal cost, centralized config
      - Integration: IaaS app reads config from SSM
      - Savings: Minimal, but avoids config management

8.2 Migrate to IaaS
   ✅ AWS Verified Permissions (AVP)
      - Reason: High cost, adds latency
      - Replacement: Application-layer RBAC middleware
      - Savings: $950/month ($11,400/year)
      - Performance: 290ms latency reduction
   
   ✅ Lambda Authorizer
      - Reason: Unnecessary with direct auth in IaaS
      - Replacement: Express.js middleware
      - Savings: $200/month latency reduction
   
   ✅ DynamoDB Tables
      - Reason: Part of core application data
      - Replacement: PostgreSQL/MySQL
      - Savings: Consistent with IaaS migration goals
   
   ✅ Lambda Functions (all 4)
      - Reason: Core application logic
      - Replacement: Express.js/NestJS controllers
      - Savings: Primary cost optimization target

8.3 Implementation Priority
   1. Set up relational database schema
   2. Implement JWT verification middleware
   3. Implement RBAC authorization middleware
   4. Migrate admin CRUD endpoints
   5. Implement pet/order CRUD operations
   6. Migrate store operations
   7. Load testing and performance validation
   8. Cutover and deprecate Lambda functions

